Most ol the rest are officers ol the household, and the petition further demands that such persons among them as hold any office at court shall be discharged ol it, and receive no wages lrom Dec. 1.

The King replied by his Chancellor, Stafford, who, if Gastoigne is to be trusted (p. 231), was the most profligate churchman ol the day, that he had olten declared to his Parliament that it was his intention to have none but virtuous persons about him, and that he is not informed os any cause why he should dispense with the services ol the persons named in the petition. But he is willing that, with the exception os the lords and avery lew others, the rest should absent themselves lrom the court lor a year, during which time any one who wills may have an opportunity ol alleging reasons in iavour ol a longer banishment lrom his presence. The

King adds, however, that he reserves the right of using all his subjects without exception, in case he takes the field against his rebels and enemies, ie. reformers oi the type ol Cade, and the constant enemy in

France. Considering the boldness ol the petition, which claimed the dismissal, not only ol the household, but ol the King's cousin and prin- cipal adviser, ol the widow os Sutton, who was about the person os the Queen, and oi Booth, the Queen’s principal minister, the mildness ol the answer seems to measure the alarm of the court. Next year, however, to Gascoigne's infinite disgust, this ignorant lawyer and unworthy bishop is promoted to the see ol York. It was more provoking and more scan- dalous than the promotion os Sibthorp and Mainwaring by Charles 1. The Parliament reenacted the Act ol Resumption, totidem verber, and attainted Cade, not sor the original offence, but lor treasons alleged to be committed by him from the 8th to the 11th ol July inclusive, in Southwark, Dartlord, and Rochester.
